{"key":"processedPost-10646631","value":{"id":10646631,"first":10635321,"last":10738753,"when":1247156809,"utime":"07/09/09 07:26 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Psuper said:</strong><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b><i>AlexP said:</i></b><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b><i>Citric said:</i></b><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b><i>RogerRabbit said:</i></b><br />The one to two hour sterilization we give is a window of opportunity to get the grains colonized before contamination sets in.&nbsp; The bacterial endospores are not all killed during a two hour cycle.&nbsp; When you 'incubate' you stimulate them to germinate, while slowing down the mycelium.&nbsp; Thus, the bacteria wins.<br />RR</blockquote><br />Which is why we soak over night, to germinate those spores, which WILL die in the pressure cooker.</blockquote><br />But some people say they are a MYTH|<br /><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/rofl.gif\" alt=\":rofl:\" title=\":rofl:\"/></blockquote><br />What? where are you getting this? no one says that. ~Pixie~</blockquote><br />Two things are important to remember here.<br />1) Bacterial endospores are not a myth.<br />2) Not all bacterial endospores will germinate during the soak, and many of those that do will produce new endospores within a few hours, which can easily be observed with a decent microscope.<br />This means that if you soak too long, you may end up with more endospores than you started with, thus defeating the purpose.<br />You'll notice in the last few years, I've stopped dwelling on 'germinating the endospores' to 'hydrating the grain' during the soak.&nbsp; If you'll hydrate the grain AND the endospores, it seems to make them more succeptable to getting nuked in the pressure cooker.<br />The fact is, mushroom growing and the science involved is currently evolving.&nbsp; Anyone who claims to know all about mushroom growing is full of shit.&nbsp; As we learn more and new things, we have to let the old pass away and embrace the new knowledge.&nbsp; The advice I give today is often different than the advice I gave even a few years ago.&nbsp; That's known as progress and learning from mistakes, not contradiction.<br />RR","title":"Re: What am I doing wrong? Four rye bags all contaminated."}}